Say I had a time domain signal x[k]x[k] wich is sparse: log(N)2log⁡(N)2 nonzero samples and the fourier transform has only a very (very!) small number of high frequency components. Are there any techniques or algorithms for recovering these high frequency components in sublinear time? (something like O(kclog(N)d)O(kclog⁡(N)d) where kk is a variable related the sparsity in either the frequency or the time domain).

The scale of invariance is not about time-shift invariance. It's about modulatory reparametrization invariance, or temporal variability invariance, or scale of information bandwidth. It's also about shift-insensitivity.

Why it's not shift-invariance

Consider a windowed sine shifted in time, and its CWT and first-order scattering:

The sine shifts, and CWT shifts by same amount. Scattering also shifts, but the relative Euclidean distance is lower:

as measured by ∥S1(x(t))−S1(x(t−τ))∥/∥S1(x(t))∥‖S1(x(t))−S1(x(t−τ))‖/‖S1(x(t))‖, where ∥⋅∥=∑|⋅|2−−−−−−√‖⋅‖=∑|⋅|2.

But that's just one row of a nice example. Keeping all else same but replacing sine with White Gaussian Noise, with T=τ=0.25 secT=τ=0.25 sec and including all orders up to second, yields 0.4710.471. An edge case, and maybe the worst case, is unit impulse - 0.5050.505.

None of these results are remotely close to what one expects of "invariance", even approximately. The following, in 1D, would qualify for approximately:

and here's 0.470.47:

Why it cannot be shift-invariance

(1) Because then we cannot have warp-stability:

∥S(x(t−τ(t)))−S(x(t))∥≤CK(τ(t))∥x∥, |τ′(t)|<1(1)(1)‖S(x(t−τ(t)))−S(x(t))‖≤CK(τ(t))‖x‖, |τ′(t)|<1

where τ(t)τ(t) is a time-warp, that includes time shifts τ(t)=τ0τ(t)=τ0. The statement is summarized as, "coefficient distance is bounded only by size of deformation, not characteristics of the signal (besides its norm)". Invariance to warps is not desired, as a sufficiently large warp will change classes (e.g. image of 5 becomes 6).

Shift-invariance hence implies warp-invariance for a subclass of warps - not just any, but the most basic one: a wide range of τ(t)τ(t) are locally constant, making scattering locally warp-invariant. This falls apart for higher orders per greater receptive fields, but point is, shift-invariance would conflict with linearizing the horizontal time-frequency component of warps.

Note, rather than "we cannot have", it's "we cannot satisfy the motivations of", since the inequality is perfectly happy with invariance.

(2) Because all scattering operators are shift-equivariant: (note, bad conv notation)

x(t)∗h(t)=y(t)|x(t)|=y(t)⇒x(t−c)∗h(t)=y(t−c)⇒|x(t−c)|=y(t−c)(2)(3)(2)x(t)∗h(t)=y(t)⇒x(t−c)∗h(t)=y(t−c)(3)|x(t)|=y(t)⇒|x(t−c)|=y(t−c)

Scattering is a stack of convolutions and complex moduli. Shift-equivariance is a known property of convolutions, (2)(2). Modulus is a pointwise operation, hence also shift-equivariant, (3)(3). A chain of shift-equivariant operators cannot produce a shift-invariant output.

(3) Because all scattering operations are smooth [informal]: to say there's "invariance for shifts under TT" would be to imply that something "special" happens at TT. Yet this would imply discontinuity and instability, which not only runs against the design of scattering, but is also absent from any operators (convolutions, modulus) or kernels (wavelets and lowpass filters). If in a loose sense, then it'd imply sharpness or rapid decay (large derivatives), which again runs against scattering's motivation to reduce variability.

So what is it instead?

It concerns information, and enhancing discriminability while reducing variability. We intentionally delay discussing "shift-insensitivity" toward the end. TODO

What is TT really? How's it measured?

To understand invariance, we first understand what imposes it - the lowpass. In time domain,

This may look surprising. It indeed was to several scattering experts. Yet it also doesn't say much: maybe it's a 3dB cutoff if we square it, or somehow related to standard deviation, or...?

Now in frequency - note it's even-symmetric so we zoom to just one side:

Here, in zoomed, one might notice a potential for exactness: the lowpass drops to (float-) zero right before bin 88. And 88 is a curious number - a power of 2, and so are T=32T=32 and len(phi)=512. Indeed,

(512/2)/T=8(512/2)/T=8

and it's no coincidence: Subsampling in time ⇔⇔ Folding in Fourier:

If unfamiliar, I recommend what's linked. In short, to losslessly subsample x by a factor k, the spectrum from either side can be non-zero only up to len(x)//2//k (for real-valued x).

Thus: TT enables ~lossless subsampling by TT. x16 lossless subsampling means that, pre-subsampling, 16 samples don't represent any variation that 1 sample can't. Variability, and information bandwidth, are cut. We elaborate further a bit later.

Discriminative invariants: selective activation

Suppose

x(t)ca1a2=((a2+1)⋅a1+2)⋅c=cos(2πfct)=cos(2πfa1t)=cos(2πfa2t)x(t)=((a2+1)⋅a1+2)⋅cc=cos⁡(2πfct)a1=cos⁡(2πfa1t)a2=cos⁡(2πfa2t)

and t=1N[0,1,...,N−1]t=1N[0,1,...,N−1], N=512N=512. With fc,fa1,fa2=185,13,2fc,fa1,fa2=185,13,2, unaveraged scattering up to third order is:

Without averaging, every order is complete and there's not much to discuss, but we inspect so we know what underlies the averaged representation. As we'll see later, every order is principally responding to a different part of input - first order to fcfc, second to fa1fa1, third to fa2fa2.

As we know, first order scattering completely captures a pure sine; all other orders are zero. A pure sine is flat in time-frequency, so each 1D coefficient only has a DC bin, which is completely captured by any lowpassing. It's hence useful to work backward from an order of interest to see what kind of signal will have significant contents up to it. Inspecting the maximum of each order:

x(t)x(t) indeed effectively terminates at third order. Changing fa1fa1 wouldn't affect first order, and fa2fa2 wouldn't affect second order - for now we'll just state it as something to keep in mind. Zeroth order is also ignored for now.

Discriminative invariants: completeness

The practical scattering pipeline is: wavelet transform input, take modulus - that's UU; lowpass + lossless-subsample UU, that's SS for the current order. The next order repeats this with UU as "input", and makes its own UU to pass to next order, and so on. The final output is only SS from each order.

What's happening, information-wise? Recall energy analysis [2]:

In steps, starting from second order for wording convenience:

  • (A) Order 2 takes unaveraged order 1 as input, CWT then modulus it, produces U2U2.
  • (B) Order 1 takes unaveraged order 1 as input, lowpass+subsamples it, produces S1S1.
  • (C) A & B together conserve energy of unaveraged order 1.
  • (D) S1S1 is output, and removed from subsequent computation. U1U1 is completely accounted for by U2U2 and S1S1. Now we have U2U2, which together with S1S1 and S0S0 account for xx, but it lacks invariance.
  • (E) Impose invariance on U2U2 while also ensuring the result completely accounts for it, by repeating (A)-(D).
  • (F) Impose invariance on all U3U3 to U∞U∞ by repeating (E): the output is S0S0 to S∞S∞ that accounts for the entirety of the input xx, while having invariance.

All of this is summarized as, where M=M= number of orders:

∑m=0M−1∥Sm∥2+∥UM∥2=∥x∥2(4)(4)∑m=0M−1‖Sm‖2+‖UM‖2=‖x‖2

As explained in [2] and just above, "flow of energy is flow of information", but we elaborate further.

Cat or dog? Idealized classifier

We simplify some properties to aid conceptualization, for now.

As we saw, every order responds to one part of input signal: fcfc, fa1fa1, or fa2fa2 - tweaking just one leaves two orders unchanged. Meanwhile, x(t)x(t) itself changes drastically when any ff is changed, likely completely: no point in xnew[n]xnew[n] equals x[n]x[n] for any nn, and the distance |xnew[n0]−x[n0]||xnew[n0]−x[n0]| for some n=n0n=n0 can be quite large.

If fa2=2fa2=2 and fa2=4fa2=4 are in same class, how do we determine this from their x0[n]x0[n] and x1[n]x1[n]? If there's two classes, in the end we're looking for a way to say "this is 00" or "this is 11", so we seek some function ΦΦ that given our input, will say Φ(x)=0Φ(x)=0 or Φ(x)=1Φ(x)=1, but must say the same thing for x0x0 and x1x1 while also not necessarily saying the same for some other x2x2.

What's a classifier?

If the input is one number and the classes are "greater than 5" and "less than or equal to 5", then Φ(x)=(x≤5)Φ(x)=(x≤5) is the solution. We've accounted for all variability, which falls on a sloped line, with a simple threshold that in 2D is a flat 0-slope line that separates the classes. With two numbers and classes separated by "sum of first point and five times the second point must exceed 10", now x[1]x[1] is five times as afflicted by measurement noise, or otherwise any change, as x[0]x[0], in effect on output. It's also possible the classes are still just "first point is greater than 5", in which case Φ(x)Φ(x) must ignore x[1]x[1]. Regardless the number of points or complexity of task, a working ΦΦ always does the same - transform xx such that there exists a separating line, or "hyperplane".

This is the gist of all classification: maximize interclass variance while minimizing intraclass variance. We require invariants, while retaining ability to discriminate. o=mean(x)o=mean(x) is very invariant - completely scrambling xx won't change oo. It's also very useless - "skate" isn't "steak".

A useful reformulation is that ΦΦ transforms xx such that LL, a linear classifier, can separate the classes; ΦΦ is then "feature extractor". Wavelet scattering is such ΦΦ.

Idealized classifier (cont'd)

If our classes indeed don't differ by fa2fa2, then scattering has provided a way to eliminate a tremendous amount of variability in xx: first and second orders will stay exactly the same (and fourth+ are zero), so we need only look at third order:

Specifically, we ignore the variability in S3S3. If instead the classes differ only by fa2fa2, we do the opposite, and it's even better - the classes are controlled by a single point, and our classifier upon o=Φ(x)o=Φ(x) becomes simply L(o)=(o[3]≥K)L(o)=(o[3]≥K) for some KK. In both cases we've reduced the dimensionality of xx from millions to a few points. (And it's why "dimension" is the size xx from a classifier's perspective - even if xx is audio, which is 1D, every point is an added degree of freedom.)

Yet, it's not quite how scattering works. Non-S3S3 don't remain exactly the same for different fa2fa2. More yet, we've only considered a "single component" signal; what if we add in another pure sine? A more complete picture is

for some x~x~ modified from xx. That is, some individual coefficients within each order don't change, while others do. This is still totally fine - "orders" just group numbers, as long as said numbers are invariant as desired, it makes no difference. But if colors represent numeric values, it's more like

that is, it's not just which coefficients activate, but by how much.

Note the precise coloring and positioning choices are completely illustrative and not meant to reflect realizable scattering configurations; what's shown is in fact impossible.

Brief note on the running example, it would make certain orders invariant to fa2fa2, and the only invariance guaranteed by scattering is for global time shifts (with T=∞T=∞).

Discriminative invariants: selective activation (cont'd)

Now actual scattering, with T=∞T=∞, sweeping fa2fa2:

Selective activation! S1S1 doesn't change, and S2S2 is mostly unchanged: the change in fa2fa2 is reflected in S3S3.

So far so good, but what's this have to do with the scale of invariance? That's up next - the other sweeps will be revisited.

To better focus and avoid clutter, the other sweeps can be clicked for viewing: fa1fa1 gif -- cc gif. They're explained later.

Temporal variability invariance

The unaveraged first-order scattering of

x(t)ca=(a+1)⋅c=cos(2πfct)=cos(2πfat)x(t)=(a+1)⋅cc=cos⁡(2πfct)a=cos⁡(2πfat)

where fc,fa=184,9fc,fa=184,9 and tt is same as before, is

where on right we supplement some info: U1_max is the max row of U1U1, phi_32 is T=32T=32 lowpass in frequency domain, and dashed vertical lines are the respective effective cutoffs.

Left shows certain irreducible variability: there's a limit to how many samples we can throw out, along time, before losing information. Right shows that, a lowpass with sufficiently high TT can eliminate this variability: the A.M. is at bin 9, so the lowpass should terminate, latest, at 8, meaning 512/2/T=8512/2/T=8, or T=32T=32.

The respective S1S1 are

and indeed, T=32T=32 eliminates the oscillations turns the rows of U1U1 into flat lines, while T=16T=16 also reduces variability but doesn't eliminate it. Left can collapse into one sample per row, i.e. one sample along time, while right also no longer needs 512, but can't do 1.

It's not about eliminating all variability, however. What really happened is that the non-DC variability of U1U1 happened to be completely contained outside of phi_32's support. Put differently, phi_32 eliminates all variability, along time, above bin 8. This means that, for all U1U1, the S1S1 is subsampleable by at least 32. That is, the variability that remains requires at most 512/32=16512/32=16 samples to fully represent. For T=16T=16, it's 3232 samples, for T=8T=8 it's 6464, and so on.

So what happens to fafa? After lowpassing, S1S1 is same as it would be without it, i.e. if we instead had just x(t)=cos(2πfct)x(t)=cos⁡(2πfct). The information on fafa is lost in S1S1. Instead, it is passed on to U2U2:

S1S1 and U2U2 together completely account for xx. However, U2U2 still takes up to 512 samples to be fully represented. So, we lowpass U2U2 with T=32T=32, and now it again takes no more than 16 samples. But again, S2S2 no longer encodes information in U2U2 above bin 8. Instead, it is passed on to U3U3.

S1S1, S2S2, and U3U3 together completely account for xx. And so on.

This process of reducing variability in UiUi to get SiSi, then recovering the variability lost by SiSi via Ui+1Ui+1, is doing something simple but powerful, that encapsulates the whole notion of "discriminative invariants" in our context: REDISTRIBUTING VARIABILITY.

Redistributing variability

  1. xx encodes all variability in 512 samples. If fcfc or fafa change, all 512 samples change.
  2. U1U1 encodes all variability in 512 samples. S1S1 encodes its own variability in 16 samples, but that's not enough to account for fafa.
  3. S1S1 encodes the variability in xx due to fcfc in 16 samples. If fcfc changes, it will take no more than 16 samples, along time, to account for it.
  4. U2U2 encodes all variability of U1U1 in 512 samples, including what S1S1 was unable to account for. To compute S1S1 and U2U2 is to impose temporal variability invariance upon U1U1, and to redistribute the remaining variability to U2U2.
  5. S2S2 encodes the variability in xx due to fafa in 16 samples. If fafa changes, it will take no more than 16 samples, along time, to account for it.
  6. The redistribution of variability continues until there's nothing left to distribute. That is, until some MM where UM=0UM=0. Then, S0S0 through SM−1SM−1 account for all of xx, using no more than 16 samples along time for each coefficient.

If what was stated is 100% correct, then U3=0U3=0 in the above example. Yet it's not. Everything is correct except the references to xx when explaining the variability that's accounted for. What's true is, at each order, all variability above bin 8 is lost, and the next order makes up for it. What's not true is, that fcfc and fafa are bound by bin 8 in their respective orders.

That's not a flaw in features or in the concept of redistributing variability. fcfc and fafa are prototypes for interpreting the behavior of different orders; the second order, for example, does serve to extract the A.M. envelopes of xx. However, scattering doesn't terminate at S2S2 because not every coefficient in U1U1 is a pure sine - and anything that's not a pure sine in order UiUi will not be a flat line in order Ui+1Ui+1.

It's the consequent behavior of the definition of the wavelet transform, which itself is more than a means for redistributing variability: the redistribution can be accomplished with any arbitrary filters that satisfy the Littlewood-Paley criterion. Wavelets are used because of other beneficial properties (e.g. warp-stability); redistribution is only one cog in the machine.

What's true in the specific example is that the vast majority of xx will in fact be encoded in S1S1 and S2S2, and as we'll see later, that's really the whole point.

How's it different from x.T?

No invertible algorithm can output fewer than NN points for NN input points for all inputs. Hence in the ideal case, scattering will output NN points, and with T=∞T=∞, completely accounting for xx while achieving shift-invariance. The concatenation of this output, with all non-time dimensions unrolled, is a 1D vector. So input's shape is (N,) or (N, 1), and output's is (1, N).

How is this different from just transposing x? From feature standpoint, we have N numbers in x, and we seek some M other numbers that aid with our task (where M can be anything). Typically, said M points are packed in a different dimensionality, e.g. 2D spectrogram for 1D audio. Yet here, one may remark, it looks like we're just moving numbers around.

The difference is, each of N numbers in x have great variability. If we just moved numbers around, then any change in x would cause an equal change in out. We're not redistributing numbers, we're redistributing variability.

Cats and dogs have four legs, two eyes and ears. Yet those legs, eyes, and ears can look very different, and have huge distances in x_cat and x_dog - with all other variability factored out (position, etc). In ideal features to a binary classifier, the distance between out_cat and out_dog will be zero, over some subset of out: this subset encodes invariance to "four legs, two eyes, two ears". Cats have whiskers, so distance between another subset of out_cat and out_dog will be great.

Not just any redistribution of variability will achieve such cat-dog invariants. |FFT(x)| and angle(FFT(x)) fully describe x, and |FFT(x)| is invariant to many kinds of variability in x, so half of our out enjoys good invariance. Yet the features are still pretty bad. The redistribution must be done "intelligently"; scattering breaks up the typical natural "knobs" in x, like carrier and modulator, into separate orders, and handles variability within each order such that changes to output for a natural deformation in input are well-behaved (warp-stability, contractiveness, etc).

What is the scale of invariance? Summary & conclusion

A change in the signal - pitch, legs and ears, etc - greatly changes its numeric representation x, even if the underlying class doesn't change (cat of different color is still cat). Ideal features are those that respond only to relevant variability, which requires invariants.

Scattering builds invariants by redistributing variability: fully informative coefficients have their temporal variability above N/TN/T in bandwidth removed, but recovered in subsequent orders, which are selectively activated and non-duplicative of former orders. This yields features whose subset doesn't change for a partial reparametrization of input, even if as a result the input changes completely (no points in common with reference input).

The complete representation which conserves input's energy is equivalently a decomposition which accounts for the entire input. The number of orders for effective "completeness" is controlled by TT: higher TT shifts accountability from lower to higher orders, increasing the range of input parameters for which a subset of coefficients are invariant.

Succinctly, TT controls invariance to input reparametrization, over a subset of the representation.

Note that there is no invariance with respect to input: the invariance is that of a part of the representation. There are only two input invariants: invariance to global phase shift, ejω0ejω0, due to modulus, and in the special case T=∞T=∞, invariance to global time shifts. That said, there doesn't appear to be a sensible restatement of the bolded sentence in terms of "scale of invariance"; it's rather "extent of invariance", where TT measures the "extent".

Lastly, "invariance to reparametrization" isn't strictly correct, as was shown earlier, but it is sufficiently accurate to be faithful to intent, unlike "time-shift invariance". "Reparametrization" in the bolded of course refers to a specific kind, that's hard to summarize, but here's an attempt: TT controls invariance to the representation-specific time-frequency-resolution-dependent amplitude- and frequency- modulatory input reparametrization, over a subset of the representation. Note the lack of comma after "representation-specific". Indeed there's heavy dependence on the quality factor (resolution tradeoff) of filterbanks at each order.

Note, this is NOT a TL;DR.

Where's the TL;DR?

There isn't one. I decided the risk of misinterpretation is too great: one could read any given summary and think it's "obvious", which almost certainly means they got the wrong idea. I've read a lot of scattering literature and haven't seen these ideas anywhere. Same words can mean different things, and I develop the necessary background to correctly interpret them.

As long as one keeps this risk in mind, the summary section is a sort of TL;DR.

Summary of summary's interpretation

TT controls invariance to the representation-specific time-frequency-resolution-dependent amplitude- and frequency-modulatory input reparametrization, over a subset of the representation

  • "representation-specific time-frequency-resolution-dependent" - amount of insensitivity for a reference input depends on the time-frequency resolution of wavelets at each order
  • "amplitude and frequency-modulatory" - CWT modulus decomposes the input into AMs and FMs, and scattering is averaging of CWT moduli of CWT moduli. AM and FM only directly maps to input at first order; subsequent orders interpret as "AM-FM of AM-FM".
  • "over a subset of the representation" - scattering is only exactly (and coincidentally, globally) invariant to global phase shifts, and for T=∞T=∞, global time shifts. For all else, certain orders, or coefficients within orders, remain approximately identical when the input is partially reparametrized.
  • "controls invariance" - "invariance" in direct sense, Sx~=SxSx~=Sx. It's also per an alternative definition, as in "CWT is translation-invariant", or "Linear Time-shift Invariant systems": invariant in sense of features, e.g. shape or energy, not changing, only shifting. This is again only approximately the case, and over a limited range of reparametrization; refer to "Addendum: errata".

"Invariance" remains not the best terminology here. "Temporal variability invariance" is an exception, but it's with respect to the representation, not the input. It becomes more faithful when accounting for the variability that's redistributed, in that the changes that otherwise don't qualify for invariance, qualify more in light of increased norms elsewhere. "Invariance" is an OK term, but only once properly interpreted, and said interpretation is difficult to summarize with each delivery in a new context. I'm unsure whether that's sufficient justification.

Literature summary proposal

In publications, we're forced to describe TT in one or two sentences. A good TL;DR isn't possible, so instead, I propose that such sentences are tactfully ambiguous and encouraging to interested readers to explore further.

Two sentences version:

TT imposes shift-insensitivity, and reparameterization invariance over a subset of scattering. Changes in input's amplitude or frequency modulations, or their modulations, are reflected in only some parts of scattering, and the unaccounted variability is redistributed to higher orders with greater TT [1].

One sentence version:

TT imposes shift-insensitivity, and invariance over a subset of scattering to reparameterization of amplitude or frequency modulations [1].

where "[1]" is a reference that explains further.

Expert consensus and history

This interpretation is mine alone, and is at odds with the rest of expert community, as far as I know. Specifically, "redistribution" isn't presented elsewhere, and "time-shift denial" contradicts established narrative. If others also say it, I'm happy to be informed.

I present what history I know, that includes my interactions with top scattering researchers and students of Stephane Mallat (who invented scattering), in a followup post: WIP
